{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_69","type":"agent_message","text":"Completed the research run and wrote the deliverables: [planning.md](/workspaces/induction-head-leakage-8afa-codex/planning.md), [REPORT.md](/workspaces/induction-head-leakage-8afa-codex/REPORT.md), [README.md](/workspaces/induction-head-leakage-8afa-codex/README.md), and [src/run_induction_leakage_experiments.py](/workspaces/induction-head-leakage-8afa-codex/src/run_induction_leakage_experiments.py). Results and figures are in [results](/workspaces/induction-head-leakage-8afa-codex/results) and [figures](/workspaces/induction-head-leakage-8afa-codex/figures), with sensitivity runs in [logs/final_run.log](/workspaces/induction-head-leakage-8afa-codex/logs/final_run.log), [logs/sweep_top2.json](/workspaces/induction-head-leakage-8afa-codex/logs/sweep_top2.json), and [logs/sweep_top3.json](/workspaces/induction-head-leakage-8afa-codex/logs/sweep_top3.json).\n\nMain conclusion: the detected induction-like heads are real and cluster in the expected GPT-2 regions, but the evidence does not support a clean claim that induction heads are a single large source of leakage. In the main paired run, ablating `L5H5` and `L5H1` reduced repeated-token bias (`0.0496 -> 0.0211`, significant), but also reduced entropy (`0.860 -> 0.819`) and worsened WikiText perplexity (`89.9 -> 169.7`). Sensitivity runs with `L5H5` and `L6H9` flipped the direction of the leakage effect, so the strongest result is that the role of these heads is heterogeneous, not monolithic.\n\nValidation: the final saved run produced `672` copy-task rows, `672` random-bias rows, and `36` WikiText rows. GPU hardware was present, but PyTorch could not use CUDA because of a driver/runtime mismatch, so all experiments ran on CPU."}}
